==English==

===Etymology===
Old French ''[[desporte]]'', from Latin ''[[deportare]]''

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

#suitable for use in athletic activities
#*''Jen has a new pair of '''sport''' shoes, and a new '''sports''' bra.''

====Synonyms====
* [[sports]]

====Translations====
;suitable for use in athletic activities (1)
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[urheilu-]] (in compounds)
{{mid}}
*German: [[Sport]]- 
{{bottom}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{countable}} any [[athletic]] activity that uses physical skills, often [[competetive]]
# {{countable}} a person who exhibits either good or bad [[sportsmanship]]
#*''Jen may have won, but she was sure a poor '''sport'''; she laughed at the loser.''
#*''The loser was a good '''sport''', and congratulated Jen on her performance.''
# {{countable}} somebody who behaves or reacts in an admirable manor, a [[good sport]]
#*''You're such a '''sport'''!  You never get upset when we tease you.''
# {{countable}} a toy; a plaything; an object of mockery.
# {{uncountable}} gaming for money as in racing, hunting, fishing
# {{cattag|biology|botany|zoology|countable}} a plant or an animal, or part of a plant or animal, which has some peculiarity not usually seen in the species; an abnormal variety or growth; a [[mutant]] 
# {{slang}} {{countable}} A [[sportsman]]; a gambler, one who consorts with less than reputable people, including prostitutes.
# {{cattag|obsolete|uncountable}} An amorous [[dalliance]].
#*''Charlie and Lisa enjoyed a bit of  '''sport''' after their hike.''

